  <!-- HOW WE TESTED -->
  <section class="problem-section">
    <div class="problem-header">
      <span class="label-pill">How we tested</span>
      <h2 class="h-lg">What to look for in a <span class="accent">marketing automation tool.</span></h2>
      <p>If you're shopping outside this list, here's the scorecard we'd use ourselves.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="ba-grid">
      <div class="ba-col after" style="grid-column: 1 / -1;">
        <ul class="ba-list">
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">01</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Demand real automation — not just scheduling</h4>
              <p>Scheduling a social post is not automation. True automation writes it, optimizes it, and publishes it based on rules you set once. Ask: "What does this tool do without me being logged in?"</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">02</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Count how many separate subscriptions you need to cover all channels</h4>
              <p>If you need an email tool + a social tool + a content tool + a local SEO tool, add up the monthly cost. One bundled platform at $99 beats four tools at $50 each.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">03</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Test the free tier before paying</h4>
              <p>Every tool in this list has either a free tier or a trial. Run it on a real business task — schedule a post, send a campaign, publish an article — before you pay. If setup takes more than an hour, that's a sign of future friction.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">04</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Prioritize content automation if content is your growth lever</h4>
              <p>Email automation helps retain customers. Content automation brings new ones in. If you're trying to grow organic traffic, lead with content (theStacc) and add email (Mailchimp or Brevo) as a secondary layer.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">05</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Check what happens to your content if you cancel</h4>
              <p>With theStacc: every article stays on your site forever. With most email tools: your data is exportable. Avoid any platform that retains ownership of your published content on cancellation.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

